1
00:00:00,655 --> 00:00:08,673
Dhammo tasa bhagavato arahato sanma sambodasa

2
00:00:09,380 --> 00:00:31,605
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambhodassam Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambhodassam Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Awakened One.

3
00:00:33,948 --> 00:00:35,590
This evening,

4
00:00:36,801 --> 00:00:40,447
slightly different, I've sort of written an actual essay.

5
00:00:41,107 --> 00:00:45,774
So I'm going to keep popping down and finding out what I'm supposed to have written.

6
00:00:46,615 --> 00:00:52,103
And I'm just wondering, how many of you have come across the law of this and that?

7
00:00:54,627 --> 00:01:00,875
Or sometimes it's better translated as the law of specific conditionality.

8
00:01:02,939 --> 00:01:03,200
Yeah?

9
00:01:03,299 --> 00:01:03,399
Yeah.

10
00:01:04,442 --> 00:01:09,326
Okay, so what I'm going to do is share my page with you.

11
00:01:09,346 --> 00:01:11,609
Here it is.

12
00:01:13,131 --> 00:01:14,191
Let's share that.

13
00:01:14,212 --> 00:01:14,492
Right.

14
00:01:15,733 --> 00:01:27,003
Okay, so this is the law of this and that, of the law of specific conditionality, iddapacchayatās.

15
00:01:27,022 --> 00:01:29,965
Now, it says when this is, that is.

16
00:01:30,606 --> 00:01:34,230
From the arising of this comes the arising of that.

17
00:01:37,213 --> 00:01:38,736
When this isn't, that isn't.

18
00:01:39,436 --> 00:01:43,840
And from the cessation of this comes the cessation of that.

19
00:01:45,882 --> 00:01:49,225
Now, if we put them in a slightly different order, it makes a bit more sense.

20
00:01:50,087 --> 00:01:53,049
From the arising of this comes the arising of that.

21
00:01:54,111 --> 00:01:57,593
From the cessation of this comes the cessation of that.

22
00:01:58,915 --> 00:02:00,796
When this is, that is.

23
00:02:01,957 --> 00:02:04,521
When this isn't, that isn't.

24
00:02:07,959 --> 00:02:09,802
Right, I'm hoping that's perfectly clear.

25
00:02:11,887 --> 00:02:22,967
So, if we take the first proposition, from the arising of that comes the arising of this, and from the stopping of that comes the stopping of this.

26
00:02:23,086 --> 00:02:30,340
Okay, so this is basically what we would recognize as our usual way of thinking about causality.

27
00:02:30,995 --> 00:02:35,520
So the thief stole from the shop and he's now in jail sometimes.

28
00:02:37,121 --> 00:02:38,502
Someone disturbed the thief.

29
00:02:39,043 --> 00:02:42,766
He failed to steal anything and the police didn't bother to investigate.

30
00:02:44,729 --> 00:02:52,296
Now, if this were the only way things happen because of things in the past, it would suggest the repetitive cosmos.

31
00:02:53,377 --> 00:02:59,044
It'd be difficult to see where creativity would come from since everything now is a product of the past.

32
00:03:00,323 --> 00:03:05,532
Now, in moral terms, that leads to determination, determinism or fatalism.

33
00:03:06,435 --> 00:03:09,019
And there would be no room for any form of free will.

34
00:03:10,301 --> 00:03:18,758
Now, indeed, at the Buddha's time, there was a person who taught this very understanding.

35
00:03:18,777 --> 00:03:20,981
He was called Mikali Gosala.

36
00:03:21,163 --> 00:03:25,389
Now, he taught that no matter what you did, you could not change your fate.

37
00:03:26,050 --> 00:03:27,432
Everything was determined.

38
00:03:28,033 --> 00:03:35,645
It was a very hard position, and the consequences of this meant that you were not responsible for your moral actions, good or bad.

39
00:03:37,227 --> 00:03:41,372
You can't blame somebody, can you, if they had to do it by fate.

40
00:03:43,796 --> 00:03:45,939
Okay, so now the second couplet says,

41
00:03:47,201 --> 00:03:52,026
presents causes that leads to present conditions, right?

42
00:03:52,046 --> 00:03:56,693
How present conditions causes lead to present conditions.

43
00:03:56,733 --> 00:04:01,758
So when this is now, that is, and when this isn't, that isn't.

44
00:04:01,777 --> 00:04:02,938
So it's all in the now.

45
00:04:03,699 --> 00:04:05,641
So this we can call synchronicity.

46
00:04:07,084 --> 00:04:12,449
How many events come together to present a particular situation?

47
00:04:13,611 --> 00:04:25,869
Now, if events arose from these sorts of conditions without past influence, there would be chaos because there doesn't seem to be any regulating factor.

48
00:04:27,610 --> 00:04:32,577
Now, from a moral point of view, that expresses itself as amorality.

49
00:04:32,658 --> 00:04:37,425
What's the point of morality when there's no guarantee it will have any effect?

50
00:04:38,670 --> 00:04:46,000
Needless to say, there was such a person who taught this Purana Kasapa.

51
00:04:46,021 --> 00:04:48,824
He had the theory of the way of non-doing.

52
00:04:49,786 --> 00:04:56,375
But what he meant by that was that actions considered good and evil carried no inherent morality.

53
00:04:57,096 --> 00:05:02,963
And thus there exists no future consequences from committing either good or evil deeds.

54
00:05:03,904 --> 00:05:05,067
So quoting him,

55
00:05:06,228 --> 00:05:21,632
Even if one were to go along the right bank of the Ganges, killing and getting others to kill, mutilating and getting others to mutilate, torturing and getting others to torture, there would be no evil for that course, no coming of evil.

56
00:05:22,572 --> 00:05:28,422
Even if one were to go along the left bank of the Ganges, giving and getting others to give,

57
00:05:28,704 --> 00:05:36,315
making sacrifices and getting others to make sacrifices, there would be no merit from that cause, no coming of merit.

58
00:05:37,357 --> 00:05:46,930
Through generosity, self-control, restraint, and truthful speech, there is no merit from that cause, no coming of merit.

59
00:05:47,350 --> 00:05:50,915
So it's a pretty stark situation.

60
00:05:52,009 --> 00:06:05,875
So how do these two forces operate, one coming from the past and all these different causes, all these different causes coming into the present?

61
00:06:06,096 --> 00:06:09,562
Okay, so an obvious example is this Zoom meeting, yeah?

62
00:06:10,353 --> 00:06:13,276
So for instance, we've all come from different causes.

63
00:06:15,098 --> 00:06:18,523
You've probably had to do various things before you set up the Zoom.

64
00:06:19,663 --> 00:06:26,892
I myself, I've got to make sure I'm plugged into Wi-Fi, sorry, internet rather than Wi-Fi.

65
00:06:26,913 --> 00:06:28,714
I've got to make sure the Zoom is updated.

66
00:06:29,855 --> 00:06:34,963
I check the talk on my tablet and then I press the necessary icons and here I am.

67
00:06:36,264 --> 00:06:39,447
So everybody will go through that sort of similar process.

68
00:06:40,829 --> 00:06:48,701
But this doesn't include the way in which we had to factor this event during our day, right?

69
00:06:48,742 --> 00:06:52,286
How future events affect present conditions.

70
00:06:52,648 --> 00:06:56,074
So lots of personal causes went into this particular event.

71
00:06:57,175 --> 00:07:04,807
And on top of that, there's all that's going on behind the scenes in the technology which is supporting this.

72
00:07:05,389 --> 00:07:08,153
And you can also include, of course, the conditions of nature.

73
00:07:09,617 --> 00:07:22,093
So, if we take a snapshot of any moment, the event will be a meeting of all past causes and present actions and situations.

74
00:07:24,035 --> 00:07:38,713
Now, this then becomes the cause for one of the causes for the next moment, where more results from different causes meet.

75
00:07:39,891 --> 00:07:43,158
So there's a constant change, constant process.

76
00:07:44,500 --> 00:07:47,607
Every event has to be singular and unique.

77
00:07:48,187 --> 00:07:52,396
It's not conceivable that the same thing could happen twice.

78
00:07:53,658 --> 00:07:54,980
Never mind Groundhog Day.

79
00:07:56,480 --> 00:08:07,975
So even though we're here seemingly in a sort of static place, the Zoom meeting is constantly changing as I'm talking and you're listening.

80
00:08:08,836 --> 00:08:13,562
The technology behind it all, we don't know what's going on there at all.

81
00:08:14,182 --> 00:08:16,125
And nature, of course, is changing.

82
00:08:16,165 --> 00:08:21,271
So you can see that we're in a process of real, quite radical change.

83
00:08:24,052 --> 00:08:28,279
So we can call this, that's right.

84
00:08:28,521 --> 00:08:35,692
So what Buddhism tends to call this is interdependency, interconnectedness, right?

85
00:08:36,133 --> 00:08:41,842
And I think it was Thich Nhat Hanh who came up with the word of interbeing when it came to the biosphere.

86
00:08:44,422 --> 00:08:48,547
And this comes out in the Mahayana's metaphor of Indra's web.

87
00:08:49,168 --> 00:09:00,260
So Indra was the king of the gods and at each vertex of his web is a jewel wherein every jewel is mirrored and so unique in itself.

88
00:09:01,623 --> 00:09:05,366
So the cosmos is holographic and in constant change.

89
00:09:06,274 --> 00:09:19,273
And Blake writes it beautifully, to see a world in a grain of sand and a heaven in a wild flower, hold infinity in the palm of your hand and eternity in an hour.

90
00:09:21,115 --> 00:09:26,604
So we can see that it might even be more apt to call it the law of specific contingency, right?

91
00:09:26,663 --> 00:09:28,907
Meaning everything coming to touch.

92
00:09:30,557 --> 00:09:33,625
Now, there might be a little, a bit of a roar in the background.

93
00:09:33,644 --> 00:09:35,008
I don't know whether you can hear it or not.

94
00:09:35,469 --> 00:09:38,495
It's the tractor coming to take these bales of hay away.

95
00:09:41,682 --> 00:09:42,023
OK.

96
00:09:43,385 --> 00:09:49,899
So which means, you see, that we can't completely with certainty say what's going to happen the next moment.

97
00:09:50,673 --> 00:09:55,080
That's how so-called unexpected events happen, right?

98
00:09:55,419 --> 00:09:56,822
Things that we don't expect.

99
00:09:57,442 --> 00:10:01,769
Earthquakes, tsunamis used to be called acts of God, but now, of course, they're acts of nature.

100
00:10:02,311 --> 00:10:09,581
And if we had an omniscient mind, we might be able to see that what is coincidence or luck is actually conditioned.

101
00:10:11,063 --> 00:10:13,187
So now on a personal level,

102
00:10:13,706 --> 00:10:18,072
This brings us always to our little special subject of death.

103
00:10:18,474 --> 00:10:21,158
So we don't know the moment of our death.

104
00:10:21,177 --> 00:10:30,250
We live on a knife edge and therefore the Buddha's admonition to practice or develop continual mindfulness.

105
00:10:34,897 --> 00:10:40,304
Now, when it comes to social, economic, political situations and all that,

106
00:10:41,922 --> 00:10:47,350
It does make us feel a little bit powerless when you see this law.

107
00:10:47,370 --> 00:10:53,061
We have such little ability to influence what's going on in the world.

108
00:10:54,523 --> 00:10:59,652
Of course, there are certain powers, certain people in power and corporations that will be capable of doing much more.

109
00:11:00,594 --> 00:11:06,023
But the overwhelming majority of us have very small influence in dealing.

110
00:11:07,825 --> 00:11:11,889
So the strength comes, of course, when we all act together.

111
00:11:12,149 --> 00:11:18,195
So that would be a case of contingency, right?

112
00:11:18,375 --> 00:11:37,393
And if we accept our personal condition as little underlings pushing up against this heavy weight, accepting our boundaries, that should undermine all this anger and outrage, grief, fear, all the negative states that come up when we're sort of going beyond the limits of our power and influence.

113
00:11:38,942 --> 00:11:41,653
And of course, that should make us more effective.

114
00:11:43,361 --> 00:11:48,884
It's better if the heart is not so embroiled but calm, the mind not so agitated but quiet.

115
00:11:50,485 --> 00:12:05,325
So it comes really from having confidence that, you know, if we have if we want to support something and we see others are going to support it, this interdependency, this interconnection will actually, you know, create a force.

116
00:12:05,345 --> 00:12:11,092
And we see that, of course, you know, in various movements around the world.

117
00:12:15,679 --> 00:12:18,043
This also brings us to the law of karma.

118
00:12:18,363 --> 00:12:26,875
And what this tells us, of course, is that it's the working of karma and what the consequence of an action will be is basically imponderable.

119
00:12:27,534 --> 00:12:32,662
There's no way you can really tell, you can really say what's going to happen.

120
00:12:35,905 --> 00:12:41,273
I mean, there's a general law that if we do something wholesome, well, then something wholesome will come of it.

121
00:12:41,332 --> 00:12:44,977
And if we do something unwholesome, there'll be an unwholesome result.

122
00:12:45,464 --> 00:12:51,750
But every action of speech and body just enters into the matrix of all relationships.

123
00:12:54,832 --> 00:12:57,355
And we can't know the effect of what will follow.

124
00:12:57,395 --> 00:13:02,221
Inwardly, it has an effect on our inner matrix of the mind.

125
00:13:03,081 --> 00:13:05,264
And we don't know what the effect of that will be.

126
00:13:05,283 --> 00:13:09,548
Except, again, that sort of general understanding.

127
00:13:10,308 --> 00:13:12,230
So here are just some examples, yeah?

128
00:13:14,235 --> 00:13:23,107
So there was a charity that I knew of which sent clothes to an African country only to upset the tailor trade and the local economy.

129
00:13:24,450 --> 00:13:27,453
Now, the charity, of course, wouldn't have known such consequences.

130
00:13:28,515 --> 00:13:39,129
But you do ask whether they actually went and interviewed the people, got some sort of understanding before they did it.

131
00:13:41,624 --> 00:13:47,635
There was also a charity way back that I remember that would ask you to support an individual child.

132
00:13:48,057 --> 00:13:49,760
And you had a relationship with that child.

133
00:13:49,780 --> 00:13:51,604
You got pictures, you got little essays.

134
00:13:52,365 --> 00:14:00,142
Unfortunately, they produced jealousy in the other children in the village who didn't get that sort of treatment.

135
00:14:00,543 --> 00:14:02,687
And there was disharmony in the community.

136
00:14:03,393 --> 00:14:05,919
So it was successful at attracting donors.

137
00:14:06,240 --> 00:14:13,479
But when that sort of Western individualism meets the more communitarian African society, well, it didn't work.

138
00:14:14,562 --> 00:14:16,827
They had to pull, they pulled a plug on it.

139
00:14:18,918 --> 00:14:25,775
There's another one about, you know, tragedy leads often to charity, to a charity or to a new law.

140
00:14:25,875 --> 00:14:30,467
So the abortion law came in and it wasn't just women's rights.

141
00:14:30,548 --> 00:14:35,981
Of course, it was there, but it was fueled by the injuries and death caused by backstreet abortions.

142
00:14:36,822 --> 00:14:43,453
And in that sort of negative sense, if this doesn't happen, this doesn't happen.

143
00:14:43,815 --> 00:14:49,645
Of course, if the law hadn't passed, we'd still be continuing with the unnecessary suffering and deaths of women.

144
00:14:52,110 --> 00:14:58,121
Now, one thing that this reminds us of is the theory of chaos.

145
00:14:58,878 --> 00:14:59,719
Yeah.

146
00:14:59,739 --> 00:15:04,085
So in the simplest way, I have no understanding of systems theory at all.

147
00:15:04,105 --> 00:15:10,413
But in the simplest of way, the example is that a butterfly, it's called a butterfly effect.

148
00:15:10,493 --> 00:15:17,182
So the flap of a butterfly with supporting conditions can end up as a hurricane.

149
00:15:21,206 --> 00:15:25,493
So even a small catalyst can bring about unpredictable effects.

150
00:15:25,912 --> 00:15:30,495
And this is, as I say, referred to as systems theory.

151
00:15:30,515 --> 00:15:38,263
I mean, an obvious place, an obvious system is, of course, the weather, which we come to know very intimately.

152
00:15:40,283 --> 00:15:47,490
There was a case of a Bosnian nationalist shot Archduke Franz Ferdinand, the heir to the Austrian throne, and his wife.

153
00:15:48,490 --> 00:15:55,277
And it's understood to be the immediate cause of the World War I, which started a month later.

154
00:15:56,658 --> 00:16:06,392
Now, he was visiting Bosnia and Herzegovina in an open carriage where there were groups of revolutionaries who wanted the country to be free from Austrian rule.

155
00:16:07,153 --> 00:16:17,006
I mean, even if he'd been just a little caution, you know, sat in a bulletproof vest or something, well, we might not have had the First World War.

156
00:16:18,369 --> 00:16:20,150
On a more positive note,

157
00:16:20,754 --> 00:16:36,062
We have, of course, Greta Thunberg, you see, skipped school at the age of 15 to demonstrate outside the Swedish parliament, calling for greater action on climate change, which eventually led to, you know, the movement of school strike for climate.

158
00:16:38,525 --> 00:16:45,278
Now, you know, there might not have been such a movement had it not been for this, for that plucky little teenager.

159
00:16:49,139 --> 00:16:58,947
Now, when it comes to our internal psychology, whatever we think, say, and act actually affects the internal matrix of our body, heart, and mind.

160
00:16:59,450 --> 00:17:07,096
And we don't know, except again, except in those broadest terms, that if we do something wholesome, then we'll have wholesome results.

161
00:17:07,738 --> 00:17:10,681
And of course, unwholesome results.

162
00:17:11,741 --> 00:17:13,784
Here are some examples that I've just plucked.

163
00:17:13,884 --> 00:17:17,247
I haven't been specific in names and whatnot.

164
00:17:18,268 --> 00:17:26,435
But there was a man I was told of, a friend of a friend, who had been temperate ever since he knew he was an alcoholic as a young man.

165
00:17:26,415 --> 00:17:31,883
Now, at retirement party, he took a sip and subsequently died of alcoholic poisoning.

166
00:17:32,824 --> 00:17:40,232
So needless to say, if he'd not had that false confidence at that moment, then he probably would have lived a long and healthy retirement.

167
00:17:42,015 --> 00:17:48,103
There was a... Oops, I've moved the thing too much.

168
00:17:48,826 --> 00:17:55,414
Yeah, there was a politician in Germany, actually, and I couldn't find the facts, but I'd seen the article.

169
00:17:56,375 --> 00:18:02,284
A leading member of the far-right racist party heard a child in distress and went to help.

170
00:18:02,684 --> 00:18:11,256
And when she saw the child was black, it so connected her with humanity, with all humanity, she dropped all her far-right beliefs.

171
00:18:12,468 --> 00:18:21,079
Now, if that little chance event, that's inverted commas, chance, had not happened, of course, she'd now be propagating far-right views.

172
00:18:24,944 --> 00:18:34,137
So even if we cannot, even in this law of unpredictability, right, of contingency,

173
00:18:34,304 --> 00:18:40,872
Yet the Buddha clearly delineates a way in which we can bring our own suffering to an end.

174
00:18:41,311 --> 00:18:41,532
Right.

175
00:18:41,553 --> 00:18:45,156
Can't do it for others, but we can do it for ourselves.

176
00:18:45,176 --> 00:18:51,605
And of course, and he describes that, of course, independent origination, which is another talk, you know.

177
00:18:54,688 --> 00:18:57,932
Sorry, that's my alarm going on.

178
00:18:58,132 --> 00:19:05,487
Now, when it comes to this specific law of conditionality, you can see how it supports the whole idea of impermanence.

179
00:19:06,127 --> 00:19:08,172
It's a real radical change.

180
00:19:09,454 --> 00:19:12,099
And there's no other way it could be, right?

181
00:19:14,284 --> 00:19:16,208
So it's not that...

182
00:19:16,508 --> 00:19:24,616
It's not that everything is impermanent, it's also that everything is therefore unsubstantial.

183
00:19:24,998 --> 00:19:26,900
There's nothing at the core.

184
00:19:27,380 --> 00:19:30,944
There's nothing there which you can point to and say, well, this is always here.

185
00:19:33,067 --> 00:19:43,578
And this, of course, refers also to ourselves as a self, which we feel is a sort of steady state within ourselves.

186
00:19:44,031 --> 00:19:46,698
But what it's saying is, is that that also changes.

187
00:19:47,398 --> 00:19:50,105
And what we're doing constantly is selfing.

188
00:19:50,464 --> 00:19:53,230
And this is what dependent origination actually points out to us.

189
00:19:55,957 --> 00:20:04,555
And that's why the Buddha is constantly telling us that this sense of self that we have, the way that we experience ourselves is delusional.

190
00:20:11,773 --> 00:20:15,038
So, where does this lead us to?

191
00:20:15,359 --> 00:20:24,032
Well, it ought to stop us, you know, being in conflict with conditions, you know, like an open radical acceptance.

192
00:20:24,394 --> 00:20:26,135
This is the way it is, right?

193
00:20:26,175 --> 00:20:29,221
This is the condition of this present moment.

194
00:20:29,240 --> 00:20:31,565
Now, that doesn't lead to hopeless resignation.

195
00:20:31,825 --> 00:20:40,178
What it should do is lead to a realistic appraisal with the way things are, and it should be a basis for action, right?

196
00:20:41,575 --> 00:20:53,446
So otherwise, if we don't do that, we just live in a morass of delusive aims, constantly going against what is actually happening and just making things worse.

197
00:20:58,011 --> 00:20:58,813
So there we are.

198
00:20:59,133 --> 00:21:00,934
And it's a wonder, isn't it?

199
00:21:01,035 --> 00:21:09,844
Like 2,500 years ago, Siddhartha Gautama, son of the Sakya tribe in North India,

200
00:21:11,258 --> 00:21:14,800
You know, left home life, went to be a salmoner, a wandering ascetic.

201
00:21:16,342 --> 00:21:22,146
You know, wondering whether there was an end to rebirth, constant round of birth, aging and death, all the suffering that it entails.

202
00:21:24,588 --> 00:21:30,513
And he not only discovered this root cause, you know, of the notion of self as false and delusive.

203
00:21:31,815 --> 00:21:39,342
He realized that there could not be an eternal soul self or integral, which is integral to the psychophysical organism.

204
00:21:39,622 --> 00:21:41,063
It's not possible.

205
00:21:41,211 --> 00:21:43,615
for it to contain something eternal.

206
00:21:45,318 --> 00:21:50,267
And one of the reasons for that is because of this specific law of conditionality.

207
00:21:51,268 --> 00:21:56,076
Now, having said that, of course, you have to remember that there is nibbana, right?

208
00:21:56,717 --> 00:22:00,282
And our spiritual aim is to find out exactly what that is.

209
00:22:03,605 --> 00:22:04,506
Well, I think that's it.

210
00:22:05,007 --> 00:22:27,080
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that this law of conditionality will allow you to modify and develop your actions to work with present conditions so that you become liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

